ntil peaks form. Drop 1 1/2 tablespoons chutney into each dessert dish. Top with 1/2 cup mousse, 1 1/2 tablespoons chutney, a dollop of whipped cream, and chocolate shavings. Cover; chill up to 1 day.'),(238235,1,'Place almonds in a dry skillet over medium heat. Cook, shaking pan often, until nuts are fragrant and lightly toasted, about 4 minutes.'),(238235,2,'Transfer to a bowl; chop finely when cool.'),(238235,3,'Bring 1 inch of water to a simmer in a small pan.'),(238235,4,'Place chocolate in a small heatproof bowl over simmering water.'),(238235,5,'Let stand until chocolate is almost melted, about 5 minutes.'),(238235,6,'Remove bowl from heat and stir chocolate until smooth.'),(238235,7,'Line a baking sheet with parchment. Working one at a time, dip about 3/4 of an apricot into chocolate, allowing excess to drip off. Gently dip chocolate-covered part of apricot into chopped nuts and transfer to baking sheet. Repeat with remaining apricots, chocolate and nuts.'),(238235,8,'Place in refrigerator until set, at least 20 minutes. Keep chilled until ready to serve.'),(238793,1,'Fry tortillas in hot oil until crisp but not browned; drain on paper towels.'),(238793,2,'Place tortillas on baking sheets, and set aside.'),(238793,3,'Fry each egg in a small amount of hot oil until eggs are set. Top each tortilla with a fried egg; spoon 2 tablespoons Mexican Sauce over top.'),(238793,4,'Sprinkle with grated cheese. Broil just until cheese melts.'),(238793,5,'Transfer to a serving platter, and serve immediately.'),(238828,1,'To make the soup, peel, pit, and coarsely chop the avocados. Purée them in a food processor with 1/2 cup of the broth, the green onion, lime juice, and tequila, scraping down the sides as needed. With the motor running, add the remaining broth. Season to taste with Tabasco and salt.'),(238828,2,'Transfer the soup to a large lipped measuring cup or bowl and refrigerate for at least 2 hours.'),(238828,3,'To make the roasted poblano cream, roast the chile under the broiler until the skin blackens, turning occasionally to roast evenly, 10 to 15 minutes total.'),(238828,4,'Put the chile in a plastic bag, securely seal it, and set aside to cool. When the chile is cool enough to handle, peel away and discard the skin.'),(238828,5,'Remove the core and seeds and chop the chile.'),(238828,6,'Put the chopped poblano in the food processor with the sour cream, cumin, and a pinch of salt. Process until very smooth, scraping the sides once or twice.'),(238828,7,'Transfer to a small bowl and refrigerate until you are ready to serve.'),(238828,8,'To serve, pour the avocado soup into tall shot glasses or espresso cups of about 1/4–cup capacity and top each with a small spoonful of the poblano cream. Top the cream with a pinch of green onion slivers and arrange on a tray to serve.'),(239102,1,'Squeeze juice from 1 lemon half into a bowl of cold water, then drop same half into water.'),(239102,2,'Cut off stem of 1 artichoke, then trim 1/4 inch from end of stem to expose inner core. Trim sides of stem down to pale inner core, then rub with other lemon half. Drop stem into acidulated water.'),(239102,3,'Cut off top inch from same artichoke with a serrated knife. Bend back outer leaves until they snap off close to base, then discard several more layers of leaves in same manner until you reach pale yellow leaves with pale green tips.'),(239102,4,'Cut yellow leaves 1/2 inch above top of artichoke bottom with a sharp knife and trim dark green fibrous parts from base and sides of artichoke with a sharp paring knife. Rub artichoke bottom all over with same lemon half, then drop artichoke into acidulated water.'),(239102,5,'Trim remaining artichokes in same manner.'),(239102,6,'Put 2 quarts water in a 4-quart pot and whisk in flour.'),(239102,7,'Whisk in oil, salt, and remaining tablespoon lemon juice and bring to a simmer.'),(239102,8,'Add artichoke bottoms and stems and simmer, partially covered, until just tender, 15 to 20 minutes.'),(239102,