the dough ball, and place it on a piece of plastic wrap. Use the wrap to mold the dough into a brick shape, approximately 8 by 2 inches by 1 inch thick. Wrap the dough in the plastic, and refrigerate for at least 1 hour or overnight.'),(734265,4,'For the filling: Cook the bacon in a large nonstick skillet over medium heat until browned and crisp, about 5 minutes.'),(734265,5,'Transfer the bacon to a medium bowl.'),(734265,6,'Drain off all but 1 tablespoon of the fat from the skillet, and return the skillet to medium heat.'),(734265,7,'Whisk in the flour, and cook, whisking constantly, until light brown, about 1 minute. Slowly whisk in the milk, and cook, whisking constantly, until thickened, about 1 minute more.'),(734265,8,'Transfer the flour-milk mixture to the bowl with the cooked bacon.'),(734265,9,'Add the egg yolk, Cheddar-Jack, Parmesan, 1/2 teaspoon kosher salt and a few grinds of pepper, and stir to combine.'),(734265,10,'To assemble: Position 2 oven racks in the top and bottom third of the oven, and preheat to 400 degrees F. Line 2 large baking sheets with parchment paper; set aside.'),(734265,11,'Cut the dough crosswise into sixteen 1/2-inch-wide rectangles. Flour a work surface and a rolling pin. Working with one rectangle at a time, roll the dough to about 4 1/2 inches by 2 1/2 inches by 1/8 inch (1 roll lengthwise with the pin and 1 roll crosswise ought to do it, then use hands to shape the dough into a rectangle).'),(734265,12,'Divide the 16 dough rectangles between the 2 prepared baking sheets.'),(734265,13,'Place about 2 teaspoons of filling at the center of each of 8 rectangles, and spread with an offset spatula, leaving a 1/2-inch border. Top with the remaining 8 rectangles. Crimp the edges together with a fork to seal.'),(734265,14,'Brush the top of each tart with the beaten egg, prick with the fork 8 times and sprinkle with a pinch of flaky sea salt.'),(734265,15,'Bake the tarts until the dough is golden brown, 22 to 24 minutes, reversing the baking sheets top to bottom halfway through.'),(734265,16,'Let the tarts cool on the baking sheets until cool enough to touch, about 5 minutes, then transfer to a wire rack.'),(734265,17,'Serve warm or at room temperature.'),(735150,1,'Warm the cream cheese in the microwave for 15 seconds then stir to soften.Melt the chocolate and allow to cool to the same temperature as the cream cheese, otherwise the chocolate will harden into lumps as it mixes with cold cream cheese.'),(735150,2,'Mix the softened cream cheese, chocolate, cocoa, stevia and peppermint essence.Cool in the fridge until firm enough to roll into balls.'),(735150,3,'Roll generous teaspoons of the truffle mixture and cool again in the refrigerator.Dust with a little cocoa powder to serve.'),(735529,1,'Coarsely grind the pork meat and fatback together into a large bowl.'),(735529,2,'Add the salt, black pepper, dried sage, cayenne, sugar and water and quickly but thoroughly mix to combine. In a hot skillet fry a tablespoon of the sausage until done, taste and adjust seasoning if necessary. Shape sausage into patties. In a skillet fry patties until browned on both sides and no longer pink in the center.'),(735529,3,'Serve hot.;'),(736098,1,'Preheat your oven to 350 degrees.Spray a 9 by 12 inch baking dish with cooking spray.'),(736098,2,'Put the bottom half of the dinner rolls in the pan.'),(736098,3,'Mix together the light mayo, hot sauce, and garlic salt together in a bowl.'),(736098,4,'Spread them over the bottom of the rolls. You may not need to use it all.'),(736098,5,'Spread 3/4 cup of mozzarella cheese over the sauce.'),(736098,6,'Add the breakfast sausage, then the bacon, then the eggs, the rest of the cheese and then top with the tops of the dinner rolls.'),(736098,7,'Brush with the melted butter.Cover the pan and bake for 20 minutes or until the cheese is melted.Separate the sliders with the edge of a spatula before removing them from the pan and serve while warm.'),(736337,1,'Watch how to make this recipe.'),(736337,2,'In a 10-inch high-sided saute pan, bring 1 inch of water (about 4 cups) to a boil over high heat.'),(736337,3,'Add the penne and the salt. Cook, stirring often, until the pasta is al dente, about 9 minutes; there should be a little water left in the pan.'),(736337,4,'Sprinkle the pecorino over the pasta; toss to coat.'),(736337,5,'Add the tomatoes, chile paste, chives, lemon zest, lemon juice and olive oil, and toss.'),(736359,1,'Place a pizza stone onto the floor of the oven and preheat the oven to 500 degrees F.'),(736359,2,'On a lightly floured surface, toss and shape the dough so that one side has a thick crust and the other thin and it looks like the crumbling Roman Coliseum.'),(736359,3,'Transfer onto a pizza paddle that has been well-dusted with semolina flour. Coat the center of the dough with marinara sauce. Cover with a layer of salami and then the cheese.'),(736359,4,'Place the peppers and avocado in a spoke pattern around the pizza. Scatter over the sausages, pine nuts, and parmesan.'),(736359,5,'Bake until the crust turns golden brown, about 8 to 10 minutes.'),(736359,6,'Share and enjoy with beer or wine or both.'),(739163,1,'Break chocolate into small pieces. In a food processor pulse together chocolate and butter until chocolate is finely chopped. In a small saucepan whisk together cream, espresso powder, and salt and bring just to a boil.'),(739163,2,'Pour hot cream mixture over chocolate mixture and pulse until smooth.'),(739163,3,'Transfer mixture to a bowl.'),(739163,4,'Let mixture stand at cool room temperature until just firm enough to pipe, about 2 hours.'),(739163,5,'Oil a large baking sheet and line with parchment paper.'),(739163,6,'Transfer chocolate mixture to a pastry bag fitted with a 1/2-inch plain tip. Pipe mixture onto baking sheet to form 1-by-1-inch cones. Chill, uncovered, until firm, at least 3 hours, and up to 1 day.'),(739163,7,'Into a small bowl, sift cocoa powder. Working with 1 smooch at a time, roll in cocoa powder to coat. Smooches keep in an airtight container at cool room temperature or chilled, 2 weeks'),(740013,1,'Position an oven rack in the top position, and preheat the oven to 375 degrees F.'),(740013,2,'Beat the cream cheese, mozzarella, sour cream, mayonnaise, Parmesan, 2 tablespoons of the breadcrumbs and 1/2 teaspoon salt in a large bowl with an electric mixer on medium high until smooth. Cover and refrigerate until ready to add the shrimp.'),(740013,3,'Melt 2 tablespoons butter in a large skillet over medium-low heat.'),(740013,4,'Add the shrimp, garlic, 1/4 teaspoon salt and the red pepper flakes, and cook, stirring frequently, until the shrimp just start to turn pink, about 2 minutes.'),(740013,5,'Add the wine, bring to a simmer and cook until the shrimp are pink and cooked through, about 2 minutes (there will be some liquid left in the skillet).'),(740013,6,'Remove the skillet from the heat, and let the shrimp cool completely.'),(740013,7,'Meanwhile, mix together the parsley, the remaining 2 tablespoons breadcrumbs and 1 tablespoon melted butter, the lemon zest and a pinch of salt in a small bowl.'),(740013,8,'Stir the shrimp, pan sauce and cream cheese mixtures together to combine; transfer to a 2-quart baking dish. (The dip and breadcrumb mixture can be covered and refrigerated overnight separately at this point.)'),(740013,9,'Sprinkle the breadcrumb mixture over the dip, and bake until hot and bubbly, 15 to 20 minutes. Switch the oven to broil, and cook until the top is golden brown, 1 to 3 minutes.'),(740013,10,'Let rest for a few minutes, then serve hot with bread and/or crackers.'),(740077,1,'Watch how to make this recipe.'),(740077,2,'Heat the coconut oil in a Dutch oven set over medium heat.'),(740077,3,'Add the leeks, carrots and celery, and saute until soft, about 5 minutes.'),(740077,4,'Add the mushrooms, garlic, thyme, bay leaves and creole seasoning; stir, and saute 2 more minutes.'),(740077,5,'Add the mushroom broth, beer, tomatoes and pinto beans. Bring to a simmer, then cover with a tight-fitting lid and cook until the beans are tender, about 1 hour.'),(740077,6,'Uncover the pot and cook until the liquid is reduced by one-third, about 15 minutes. Season with 2 tablespoons of the miso paste and some pepper. Taste and add more miso as needed.'),(740270,1,'Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil.'),(740270,2,'Add the spaghetti and cook until al dente, stirring often, 8 to 10 minutes.'),(740270,3,'Drain well, reserving 2 cups of the pasta water.'),(740270,4,'Heat a large skillet over medium heat.'),(740270,5,'Add the olive oil, garlic and Thai chile, and cook until softened and fragrant, 2 minutes.'),(740270,6,'Add the edamame, scallions, butter and salt; cook for an additional minute, until the edamame is heated through and the scallions are soft.'),(740270,7,'Add the drained pasta and the shiso, sesame seeds and the reserved pasta water. Simmer for about 1 minute, tossing gently, until the sauce is creamy.'),(740270,8,'Serve topped with a small dollop of tobiko.'),(741080,1,'Position oven racks in the top and bottom thirds of the oven, and preheat to 425 degrees F. Line 2 baking sheets with parchment.'),(741080,2,'Whisk together the flour, baking soda and salt in a large bowl. Beat the butter and both sugars with an electric mixer on medium-high speed in a second large bowl until light and fluffy, about 4 minutes.'),(741080,3,'Add the eggs to the butter mixture, one at time, beating after each addition to incorporate; beat in the vanilla. Reduce the speed to medium, add the flour mixture, and beat until just incorporated. Stir in the chocolate chips.'),(741080,4,'Scoop 12 heaping tablespoons of dough onto each prepared baking sheet about 2 inches apart.'),(741080,5,'Roll each into a ball with slightly wet hands.'),(741080,6,'Bake until the cookies are golden and crunchy on the outside, 8 to 10 minutes, rotating the baking sheets halfway through.'),(741080,7,'Let the cookies cool for a few minutes on the baking sheets, then transfer them to a rack to cool completely.'),(741080,8,'When the baking sheets have cooled completely, scoop the remaining dough onto 1 sheet and bake. Store the cookies in a tightly sealed container at room temperature for up to 5 days.'),(741159,1,'In a large bowl combine all of the ingredients except mint and parsley. In batches if necessary, ladle about 1/3 of the soup into a food processor and pulse, leaving mixture somewhat lumpy.'),(741159,2,'Add back to the unpureed soup and continue until desired consistency is achieved. Reseason if necessary.'),(741159,3,'Add herbs and stir. Ladle into chilled soup bowls and garnish with dollop of creme fraiche and additional herbs.'),(741497,1,'Brine: in a nonreactive container or resealable plastic bag combine the spring water, Gewurztraminer, sugar, citrus zest and juice, grapeseed oil, salt, peppercorns, and bay leaves. Set aside.'),(741497,2,'Remove the pork loin from the package and pat dry to remove all the liquid, wash the pork loin under room temperature water and repeat the pat dry method. Next, trim some fat from the top of the pork loin and place the loin in the brine. Refrigerate for 24 hours below 41 degrees F or lower.'),(741497,3,'Remove the pork and discard the brine. Lightly pat it dry and place it on a flat 1/2 sheet pan, lightly wrap in plastic, and put into the freezer. When the pork is slightly frozen, using a machine slicer (deli slicer) slice the frozen pork paper thin. Portion the pork loin into 6 servings of 5.6 ounces each if just a little heavy that is fine you have room for error with the extra ounces. Put each portion on small deli sheets or parchment paper and place them in the refrigerator until ready for use. Be sure to properly sanitize the deli slicer and wash it in hot soapy water.'),(741497,4,'Finishing the sandwich: Preheat a large flat top \"Philly Style\" gas griddle about 26 by 18-inches to 350 degrees F for 5 minutes.'),(741497,5,'Pour 4 tablespoons grapeseed oil in the center of the griddle, spread evenly and let the oil get hot.'),(741497,6,'Place the julienne onions on 1 side of the griddle and let them caramelize about 4 minutes. On the other side of the griddle, place the ground bratwurst and let cook through to an internal temperature of 155 degrees F. Chop the brats into smaller crumbles. When the brats and the onions are fully cooked, about 5 minutes more, toss them together and to one side of the griddle on low-heat (160 degrees F for hot holding). On the side that you just removed the brat and onion mixture, place the kraut and the julienned apples and cook until tender, another 4 minutes. When the kraut and the apples are fully cooked toss them together with the onions and brat\'s. Deglaze with the beer and reduce until it has evaporated. Hold the apple mixture with the onion and brats on the cooler part of the griddle.'),(741497,7,'Remove the shaved pork loin from the refrigerator.'),(741497,8,'Drizzle the last 4 tablespoons grapeseed oil on the part of the griddle that is at 350 degrees F and cook the shaved pork loin about 5 minutes. Lightly rough chop the shaved pork loin \"Philly style\"- place 1 spatula on a section of the pork loin and hold firmly and with a second spatula pull gently apart (pull away from each other and away from your body). When the shaved chopped pork loin is fully cooked and no visible blood, be sure it is fully chopped \"Philly style\" toss with the warm kraut, onion, apple, and brats, and section into 6 (6-ounce) portions on the griddle. Top each portion with 2 ounces Limburger cheese.'),(741497,9,'Place 1 sliced pumpernickel hoagie roll on top of the melted cheese/pork portion and place a spatula under it.'),(741497,10,'Place one hand on top of the roll and flip sunny side up while catching the pork-melted cheese stuffed roll in the same hand that you use to place on the roll.'),(741497,11,'Serve with mustard, German pickles and German beer.'),(741527,1,'Chef\'s Note: Do not try to attempt cooking this on a motorcycle. Use an indoor oven instead.'),(741527,2,'Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Prepare 2 sheets of aluminum foil to use as pouches for the trout fillets. First brush a little bit of the oil on each piece of foil to prevent the fillets from sticking.'),(741527,3,'Place the trout fillets in the center of each piece of foil.'),(741527,4,'Sprinkle the fillets with salt and pepper.'),(741527,5,'Drizzle the remaining olive oil on top of the fillets. Then place the mushrooms, onion, and spinach on top of the trout.'),(741527,6,'Sprinkle with the cilantro leaves and ginkgo.'),(741527,7,'Fold the foil bag on all sides to create a pouch. Before sealing it completely, pour the wine into each pouch. Seal the top of each pouch tightly and place them on a baking sheet.'),(741527,8,'Place the baking sheet into the oven. Cook for 20 to 25 minutes or until the trout is fully cooked and flakes apart.'),(743154,1,'Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F.'),(743154,2,'Combine the allspice, oregano and garlic powder in a bowl. Pierce the pork all over with a fork. Season with 1/2 teaspoon salt and a few grinds of pepper; rub with the spice mixture.'),(743154,3,'Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a large ovenproof nonstick skillet over medium-high heat.'),(743154,4,'Add the pork and cook, turning, until browned all over, about 5 minutes.'),(743154,5,'Transfer the skillet to the oven. Cook until a thermometer inserted into the center of the pork registers 145 degrees F, about 20 minutes.'),(743154,6,'Transfer to a cutting board and let rest 5 minutes.'),(743154,7,'Meanwhile, heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a medium saucepan over medium-high heat.'),(743154,8,'Add the couscous and cook, stirring, until toasted, 5 minutes.'),(743154,9,'Add 1 3/4 cups water, 1/2 teaspoon salt and a few grinds of pepper. Bring to a simmer, then reduce the heat to low; cover and cook until the liquid is absorbed, about 15 minutes.'),(743154,10,'Fluff the couscous with a fork; let cool.'),(743154,11,'Add the feta, cucumbers, herbs, sun-dried tomatoes, lemon juice and the remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil; toss. Season with salt and pepper.'),(743154,12,'Serve with the pork and lemon wedges.'),(743154,13,'Photograph by Charles Masters'),(743502,1,'For the cookies: Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper and grease with butter.'),(743502,2,'In a stand mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, combine the butter, brown sugar, granulated sugar and vanilla. Beat on medium speed until light and fluffy.'),(743502,3,'Add the eggs, one at a time, scraping down the sides of the bowl after each addition.'),(743502,4,'In a medium bowl, sift together the flour, baking powder, baking soda, cinnamon, ginger and salt.'),(743502,5,'Add the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients, and mix on low speed until just combined, being careful to avoid over-mixing. Fold in the oats, apples, cherries and dates. Portion out the dough onto the prepared baking sheet (about 20 cookies), and bake until the edges are golden, 10 minutes.'),(743502,6,'For the filling: In a stand mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, beat the cream cheese, butter and confectioners\' sugar on low speed until smooth and fluffy.'),(743502,7,'Transfer the filling to a pastry bag and pipe the filling onto half of the cookies.'),(743502,8,'Place the other half of the cookies on the filling to make the sandwiches.'),(745381,1,'Grease a 10-inch spring form pan and line with parchment paper.'),(745381,2,'In a food processor grind the hazelnuts and 3/4 cup sugar together, pulsing to avoid over blending so it does not become a paste. Whip the cream using a mixer fitted with a whisk attachment or a hand mixer, until fluffy, soft peaks.'),(745381,3,'Transfer to the refrigerator.'),(745381,4,'In a clean dry bowl, whip the egg whites until soft peaks form.'),(745381,5,'Add the vanilla extract and 1/4 cup sugar and continue whipping until glossy and stiff, about 30 seconds more. Fold into the whipped cream, then fold in the ground nut mixture. Spoon the mixture into the spring form pan. Smooth the top. Freeze at least 4 hours or overnight.'),(745381,6,'Warm Glossy Chocolate Sauce: In the top half of a double boiler, combine the 2 chocolates over simmering water. Stir constantly until melted, then whisk in the corn syrup and water.'),(745381,7,'Whisk until smooth and shiny.'),(745381,8,'When ready to eat, remove the collar and serve frozen with chocolate sauce.'),(745381,9,'*RAW EGG WARNING'),(745381,10,'Food Network Kitchens suggest caution in consuming raw and lightly-cooked eggs due to the slight risk of Salmonella or other food-borne illness. To reduce this risk, we recommend you use only fresh, properly-refrigerated, clean, grade A or AA eggs with intact shells, and avoid contact between the yolks or whites and the shell.'),(746014,1,'Season fillets with salt and pepper.'),(746014,2,'Heat a heavy saute pan over medium high heat. Coat edges of fillet with a thin layer of mustard, approximately 2 tablespoons. Dredge edges of filet in herbs to coat evenly. Sear fillet, 4 to 6 minutes per side, depending on the thickness of the meat.'),(746014,3,'Remove cooked fillet. Lower heat to medium.'),(746014,4,'Add shallots and saute until translucent. Deglaze pan with white wine.'),(746014,5,'Add 2 tablespoons mustard. Reduce wine to consistency of a rich sauce. If desired, remove the pan from the heat and whisk butter into the sauce.'),(746014,6,'Serve immediately.'),(746663,1,'Resift flour with sugar, baking powder and 3/4 teaspoon of salt.'),(746663,2,'Combine melted butter, egg and yolk and whisk in milk. Preheat the griddle'),(746663,3,'With a few swift strokes fold the wet ingredients into the dry ones. Do not overmix; keep the batter lumpy so they will turn out light. Cook the pancakes on the griddle, using a scant 1/4 cup for each pancake. Turn them over when bubbles form over the entire surface of the pancake and cook for a few minutes on the other side.'),(746663,4,'Serve hot with maple syrup. For dinner, serve hot with a saute of apples and raisins and along with either slices of bacon or topped with cottage or ricotta cheese.'),(746985,1,'Watch how to make this recipe.'),(746985,2,'Place the egg yolks, sugar, and Marsala wine in a large heat-proof glass bowl and whisk them together.'),(746985,3,'Place the bowl on a pan of simmering water to make a double boiler and whisk the mixture almost constantly for 5 to 7 minutes, until it expands in volume and becomes thickened. You\'ll see the froth disappear and the whisk will leave a little trail in the mixture. Don\'t walk away from it or youll end up with scrambled eggs! Off the heat, whisk in the vanilla and almond extracts. Set aside for 30 minutes to cool to room temperature, whisking once or twice as it cools.'),(746985,4,'Place the cream in the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with the whisk attachment (you can also use a hand mixer) and beat it just until it forms firm peaks. With a rubber spatula, carefully fold the cream into the Marsala mixture. Spoon half of the mixture into each of 4 or 5 decorative glasses (depending on the size), sprinkle each with 1 tablespoon of crushed Amaretti, and spoon the rest of the mixture on top.'),(746985,5,'Sprinkle with the remaining Amaretti crumbs, cover with plastic wrap, and chill for a few hours or overnight.'),(746985,6,'Serve cold.'),(749151,1,'Place the dried fruit and raisins in a heatproof bowl and cover with boiling water. Allow to stand for 30 minutes, or until the fruit has plumped.'),(749151,2,'Drain off all the soaking liquid, reserving 1 cup.'),(749151,3,'Place the fruit and the reserved soaking liquid in a large saucepan.'),(749151,4,'Add the wine, ginger, cloves, star anise, and cinnamon stick, place over medium heat, and bring to a boil. Immediately lower the heat to a low simmer, cover, and simmer for about 15 minutes, or until the fruit is quite soft.'),(749151,5,'Remove from the heat and drain well, discarding the spices.'),(749151,6,'Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 450 degrees F.'),(749151,7,'Lightly butter a baking sheet.'),(749151,8,'Spread the poached fruit and the nuts out on the baking sheet, leaving space between the fruit.'),(749151,9,'Brush the tops with the melted butter. Roast for 10 minutes, or until the fruit is just beginning to color.'),(749151,10,'Serve in individual bowls, drizzled with caramel sauce.'),(749151,11,'Combine the brown and granulated sugars with 1 cup cold water in a heavy medium saucepan over medium heat and bring to a boil. Boil for 12 minutes, or until the syrup is a rich caramel color, brushing down the sides of the pan with a wet pastry brush from time to time to dissolve any sugar crystals that form.'),(749151,12,'Taking care as the syrup may bubble over, whisk in the corn syrup, lemon juice, and vanilla and bring to a simmer. Carefully whisk in the cream, bring to a boil, and boil gently for 10 minutes, or until the sauce is thick.'),(749151,13,'Whisk in the butter and serve hot.'),(749408,1,'Cut the tips off the wings and discard.'),(749408,2,'Cut remaining chicken wings in half at the joint. Deep fry wings in about 2 inches of oil in skillet until done.'),(749408,3,'Drain on paper towels. Melt butter and hot sauce together. Dip fried wings into the sauce.'),(749408,4,'Serve with a spicy blue cheese dip or dressing and celery sticks.;'),(749408,5,'In a small bowl mix together all ingredients.'),(749408,6,'Serve with chicken wings.;'),(749761,1,'Special equipment: melon baller'),(749761,2,'For the creme brulee: In a medium saucepan, bring the cream, sugar and vanilla bean to a boil.'),(749761,3,'Add the egg yolks and continue to cook, whisking until slightly thickened.'),(749761,4,'Remove the pan from the heat, strain and set aside for later use.'),(749761,5,'For the caramel: Stir together the milk and sugar in a large, heavy-bottomed pot. (Make sure the liquid only goes three-quarters of the way up the sides, as it will froth when the baking soda is added.)'),(749761,6,'Add the vanilla extract, salt, cinnamon stick and vanilla bean with seeds if using.'),(749761,7,'Heat the mixture over medium-high heat, constantly stirring, and bring to a boil, about 15 minutes. Keep your eyes on the pot-- it boils over easily and quickly! Quickly remove from the heat and add the baking soda to the pot. The mixture will rise and become frothy, just keep stirring the mixture.'),(749761,8,'Return the pot to medium heat, and stir frequently, about every 10 minutes. Make sure the milk stays at a gentle simmer rather than a raging boil, and stir across the bottom of the pot to make sure the mixture is not scorching. Adjust the heat as needed. Cook until the milk starts to turn golden brown, about 1 hour 30 minutes.'),(749761,9,'Remove the cinnamon stick and the vanilla pod. At this point, it will start to thicken quickly, so it\'s important to keep stirring so the milk doesn\'t burn on the bottom of the pan. Keep stirring until the mixture is a rich brown and thick enough to coat the back of the spoon, 15 to 30 minutes.'),(749761,10,'Cool the sauce slightly and then pour into an airtight container. Store the mixture in the refrigerator for up to 1 week.'),(749761,11,'Preheat the oven to 300 degrees F.'),(749761,12,'Using a melon baller, hollow out the crab apples. Fill the centers with the creme brulee and bake until the creme brulee is set. Chill overnight.'),(749761,13,'Reheat the caramel until soft enough for dipping. Dip the stuffed apples using a stick or fork. Chill for 1 hour before serving.'),(749813,1,'Combine the mangoes, sweet peppers, green onions, Key lime juice, cilantro, jalapeno, garlic and salt in a medium bowl and toss gently.'),(749813,2,'Let stand for 30 minutes at room temperature (place in the fridge if it will be longer).'),(750203,1,'Bring 3 cups water and the ginger to a boil in a medium pot.'),(750203,2,'Add the tea bags, take the pot off the heat, and steep for 4 minutes.'),(750203,3,'Remove the tea bags and stir in the sugar until dissolved. Cool; discard ginger.'),(750203,4,'Put the tea, peach nectar, tequila and lime juice in a pitcher and stir to combine. Stir in the peach slices.'),(750203,5,'Serve over ice.'),(750778,1,'For the Pears: Put wine, juice, cinnamon, lemon juice, and sugar substitute in a pot, and bring to a boil. Take off the heat and add some clear glaze to slightly thicken the mixture.'),(750778,2,'Add the sliced pears to the mixture and cool.'),(750778,3,'Pastry Cream: Bring to a boil the milk, margarine, and split vanilla bean.'),(750778,4,'Combine eggbeaters, sugar, and cornstarch and add to boiled milk. Cook until thick. Fold pastry cream with some whipped cream.'),(751252,1,'Puree 2 cans of black beans in 2 cups water in food processor.'),(751252,2,'Heat the lard or other fat in a large saucepan over medium heat.'),(751252,3,'Saute the onions with the salt and cumin until golden, about 10 minutes.'),(751252,4,'Add the beans and continue cooking over medium heat, stirring frequently, until the liquid evaporates and the beans form a creamy mass that pulls away from the bottom and sides of the pan, about 15 minutes.'),(751252,5,'Serve immediately.'),(752205,1,'Wash and stem the mint leaves, reserving 6 whole sprigs for garnish.'),(752205,2,'Place the mint leaves in the bottom of a sturdy pitcher and add the sugar. Mash the mint leaves and sugar together, using the tip of a wooden spoon -- this extracts the mint oils.'),(752205,3,'Add the lime juice and rum and stir until the sugar is dissolved. The recipe can be made several hours ahead to this stage. However, expect some discoloring in the mint leaves if you make the mojitos more than 20 minutes ahead.'),(752205,4,'Just before serving, add the club soda and gently stir to mix. Partially fill 6 highball glasses with ice.'),(752205,5,'Add the mojito mixture and garnish each glass with a sprig of fresh mint.'),(753436,1,'Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F.'),(753436,2,'Place the tomatillos, apples, garlic, jalapenos and onion on a baking sheet; toss with the olive oil, 2 teaspoons salt and 1 teaspoon pepper. Roast until the tomatillos are softened and slightly charred, about 20 minutes. Peel the garlic.'),(753436,3,'Let the roasted vegetable mixture cool to room temperature.'),(753436,4,'Puree the roasted vegetable mixture and cilantro in a blender until smooth.'),(753436,5,'Add 2 to 3 tablespoons water to loosen, if needed. Season with salt and pepper.'),(753729,1,'Rinse the chicken well under cold running water and pat dry with paper towels. Season generously with salt and pepper. In a large heavy skillet, heat the olive oil over medium/high heat. Brown the chicken pieces evenly on all sides, then transfer to a covered heatproof casserole.'),(753729,2,'Add the onions and carrots to the hot skillet and cook, stirring occasionally, for about 10 minutes, until golden.'),(753729,3,'Transfer them to the casserole with the chicken.'),(753729,4,'Place the potatoes around the edges of the casserole and again season with salt and pepper.'),(753729,5,'Add the bay leaf.'),(753729,6,'Pour off most of the fat from the skillet and, over high heat, deglaze it with the white wine. Cook, stirring and scraping the bottom and sides of the pan to release all the flavorful bits into the liquid, for about 3 minutes.'),(753729,7,'Pour the wine over the chicken, add the stock and bring up to the boil. Reduce the heat to very low, cover and simmer for 25 to 30 minutes, until the chicken thighs test done. Check the pan occasionally to make sure the liquid is kept at a slow simmer. If it boils the chicken will be tough.'),(753729,8,'Transfer the chicken and vegetables to a platter with a slotted spoon and discard the bay leaf.'),(753729,9,'To make the picada: combine the almonds and garlic in a food processor and process them to a fine paste.'),(753729,10,'Add the saffron and the hardboiled egg yolks only, process again and add enough of the liquid from the casserole to make a smooth paste. Return the casserole to mediumhigh heat and whisk the picada into the cooking liquid. Simmer until the sauce is reduced to about 3 cups, and taste for seasoning. Return the chicken and vegetables to the pan and turn to coat them with the sauce and heat through.'),(753729,11,'Serve in the pan, sprinkled with the egg whites.'),(754332,1,'Fill a large pot with water; add the octopuses, white onion halves and bay leaf. Bring to a boil, then reduce the heat to medium. Simmer until the octopuses are very tender, about 2 hours.'),(754332,2,'Drain, discarding the onion and bay leaf.'),(754332,3,'Let the octopuses cool; cut into small pieces.'),(754332,4,'Melt the butter in a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat.'),(754332,5,'Add the red onion and cook, stirring, until fragrant, about 6 minutes.'),(754332,6,'Add the garlic and chiles and cook, stirring, until tender, 3 more minutes.'),(754332,7,'Add the octopuses and saute until lightly browned, about 5 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.'),(754332,8,'Serve in tortillas; top with cilantro and diced white onion.'),(754332,9,'Serve with lime wedges.'),(754332,10,'Photograph by Dave Lauridsen'),(754841,1,'Preheat oven to 425 degrees F.'),(754841,2,'Place clean salmon fillet on an oven-proof pan.'),(754841,3,'Spread fresh herbs on top of fillet and season with salt and pepper.'),(754841,4,'Pour olive oil all over the fish, add white wine and chicken broth.'),(754841,5,'Bake in oven until fish is cooked through, about 8 to 10 minutes.'),(754841,6,'Remove salmon to a serving dish and reduce the sauce to desired consistency.'),(754841,7,'Pour sauce over the fish and drizzle with olive oil.'),(755378,1,'Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F.'),(755378,2,'Mix together the breadcrumbs, eggs, cheese, chickpeas, pine nuts, raisins, garlic, parsley, salt, pepper, broccoli and cauliflower. Refrigerate for 15 minutes. Scoop and roll the mixture into about 2.5-ounce balls.'),(7