archment paper. In a stand mixer bowl fitted with a beater attachment, add the flax, starch, and almond milk.'),(836847,2,'Mix on low speed until fully combined.'),(836847,3,'Add the peanut butter, coconut oil, molasses, vanilla extract, and stevia extract.'),(836847,4,'Mix again until fully combined. In a large bowl, stir together the oats, erythritol, baking powder, baking soda, and salt. Dump the dry ingredients into the stand mixer bowl and mix until fully combined, scraping down the sides of the bowl if necessary. Scoop the cookie dough onto the prepared cookie sheets (I used a black size 30 scooper/disher). Flatten the cookie dough mounds slightly, then bake for ~12 minutes.'),(836847,5,'Let cookies cool, then serveand enjoy!'),(837481,1,'Brown beef and sausage, drain grease.'),(837481,2,'Add onions and potatoes to meat mixture, stir and cook for 3-4 minutes on medium-high heat. Continue stirring to lightly fry mixture evenly.'),(837481,3,'Add tomatoes and tomato sauce and stir to combine.Cover and boil over medium for about 15 minutes or until potatoes are tender.While Goulash is cooking, prepare pasta according to package instructions.'),(837481,4,'Serve the Goulash over pasta and enjoy!'),(839159,1,'Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a large skillet over medium high heat.'),(839159,2,'Add ground beef and cook until beef has browned, about 3-5 minutes, making sure to crumble the beef as it cooks; stir in taco seasoning.'),(839159,3,'Drain excess fat; set aside.'),(839159,4,'Heat tortillas according to package instructions.'),(839159,5,'Heat nacho cheeseaccording to package instructions.Working one at a time, place ground beef mixturein the center of each tortilla. Top with nacho cheese and tostada shell.'),(839159,6,'Spread sour creamin an even layer over the tostada shell; top with lettuce, tomato and cheese.Repeat with remaining tortillas.Fold the edges up and over the center. Continue to work your way around the tortilla, folding as tight as possible.'),(839159,7,'Heat remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil ina large skillet.'),(839159,8,'Place wrap seam-side down and cook until theunderside is golden brown, about 2 minutes. Flip and cook wrapon the other side, about 1-2 minutes longer.'),(839159,9,'Serve immediately.'),(841739,1,'1Prepare the ingredients:Wash and dry the fresh produce. Peel and mince the garlic.'),(841739,2,'Drain and rinse the chickpeas; mince the chickpeas then, using the flat side of your knife, smash them into a rough paste. Mince the chives. Medium dice the eggplant, red bell pepper and zucchini. Peel and small dice the onion.2Start the ratatouille: In a medium pot, heat 2 teaspoons of olive oil on medium until hot.'),(841739,3,'Add the onion  and season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, 2 to 3 minutes, or until fragrant and softened.'),(841739,4,'Add a little more oil and the eggplant, bell pepper and zucchini. Season with salt and pepper and cook, stirring occasionally, 5 to 8 minutes, or until softened. Stir in the garlic and as much of the red pepper flakes as youd like, depending on how spicy youd like the dish to be. Cook 30 seconds to 1 minute, or until fragrant.3'),(841739,5,'Add the tomatoes & seasonings:To the pot of vegetables, add the diced tomatoes, red wine vinegar and  cup of water; season with salt and pepper and cook 7 to 9 minutes, or until slightly reduced in volume and the vegetables are tender.'),(841739,6,'Remove from heat and stir in half of the Parmesan cheese.4Make & form the fritters:While the ratatouille cooks, in a medium bowl, combine the mashed chickpeas, chickpea flour, chives, 2 tablespoons of water and all but a pinch of the remaining Parmesan cheese (save the rest for garnish). Season with a generous amount of salt and as much pepper as youd like. Using your hands, divide the mixture into 6 equal parts and form into patties.5Cook the fritters:In a large pan (nonstick, if you have one), heat 2 teaspoons of oil on medium-high until hot. Once the oil is hot 